const faqSchema={"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I refinance the house during a divorce before it's finalized?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, you can refinance before the divorce is final, but it requires careful coordination with your legal proceedings. Some couples refinance before finalizing to take advantage of combined income qualification or lock in favorable rates. However, the refinance must align with your divorce settlement terms. Consult both your attorney and mortgage advisor to ensure the timing works for your situation. In some cases, waiting until after finalization provides cleaner separation."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How soon after divorce can I qualify for a mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You can typically qualify for a mortgage immediately after divorce if you meet standard lending criteria\u2014sufficient income, good credit, and acceptable debt-to-income ratio. There's no mandatory waiting period after divorce itself. However, if your credit score dropped during the separation or you're now relying on alimony or child support for qualification, you may need to wait several months to establish a payment history. Each situation is unique, so schedule a consultation to assess your specific timeline."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What if my ex-spouse won't cooperate with refinancing?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "If your divorce decree requires refinancing but your ex-spouse refuses to cooperate, you have legal options. First, work with your attorney\u2014they can petition the court to enforce the decree. In some cases, courts can order cooperation or impose penalties for non-compliance. From a mortgage perspective, you may need to explore assumption options or seek court intervention for signing authority. This is a legal matter as much as a financial one, requiring coordination between your attorney and lender."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Do I have to refinance if the divorce decree says I get the house?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "While the divorce decree establishes legal ownership, it doesn't automatically remove your ex-spouse from the mortgage obligation. The lender isn't bound by divorce decrees\u2014both original borrowers remain liable until the mortgage is refinanced or paid off. If you don't refinance, your ex-spouse stays on the loan and their credit remains at risk if you miss payments. Most divorce settlements include a timeframe requirement for refinancing specifically to resolve this issue. Check our conventional loan refinance options to start the process."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I use alimony or child support income to qualify for a refinance?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, alimony and child support can be used to qualify for a mortgage refinance, but lenders have specific requirements. Typically, you must receive the payments consistently for several months to a year (depending on the lender) and provide documentation that payments will continue for at least several more years. You'll need copies of the divorce decree, evidence of payment history (bank statements showing deposits), and sometimes verification from your ex-spouse or attorney. The divorce buyout calculator can help you see how this income affects your qualification."}}]};
const breadcrumbSchema={"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "BreadcrumbList", "itemListElement": [{"@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://stairwaymortgage.com/"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Blog", "item": "https://stairwaymortgage.com/blog/"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Divorce Mortgage Guide: Buyout, Refinance, and Property Division Strategies"}]};
